{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01H46TxZ9n3n6frBG6sWHm8z","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect! I've read both test files completely. Here's a summary of what I found:\n\n## Test Infrastructure Overview\n\n### **lordofrngs.ts** (Lines 1-541)\nThe Lord of RNGs tests are focused on **state transitions and escrow management**, NOT on VRF testing (since Lord doesn't use VRF in iteration 6). Key patterns:\n\n**Test Setup:**\n- Uses `startAnchor()` with bankrun provider\n- Creates test context with pre-funded accounts\n- Uses PDA helpers (`getConfigPda`, `getRoundPda`)\n\n**Key Test Areas:**\n1. **initialize_config** — Creates config with treasury and paused=false\n2. **create_round** — Tests round creation, escrow balance validation, tier validation\n3. **join_round** — Tests phase transitions (Waiting → Active when 2nd player joins), player array management, max 20 player cap\n4. **buy_more_entries** — Tests entry count increases and escrow updates\n5. **Phase Validation** — Tests InvalidPhase errors for locked rounds (though VRF-based lock tests are deferred)\n\n**Notable Patterns:**\n- Escrow validation: `rent + (num_entries × entry_amount)` \n- Clock manipulation is NOT used (no countdown testing yet)\n- Round counter per tier tracking\n- Max player limit enforcement (20)\n\n---\n\n### **coinflip.ts** (Lines 1-1010)\nThe Coinflip tests show **full VRF integration** and are directly applicable to Lord. Key patterns:\n\n**Mock VRF Setup (Lines 41-56):**\n```typescript\n// RANDOMNESS_HEADS: byte[0]=2 → 2%2=0=HEADS\nconst RANDOMNESS_HEADS = (() => {\n  const buf = Buffer.alloc(32);\n  buf[0] = 2;\n  return buf;\n})();\n\n// RANDOMNESS_TAILS: byte[0]=1 → 1%2=1=TAILS\nconst RANDOMNESS_TAILS = (() => {\n  const buf = Buffer.alloc(32);\n  buf[0] = 1;\n  return buf;\n})();\n\n// RANDOMNESS_UNFULFILLED: all zeros\nconst RANDOMNESS_UNFULFILLED = Buffer.alloc(32);\n```\n\n**Mock Orao Accounts Setup (Lines 124-149):**\n```typescript\nconst context = await startAnchor(\"./\", [], [\n  { address: opponent.publicKey, info: fundedAccountData() },\n  { address: treasury.publicKey, info: fundedAccountData() },\n  // Mock Orao accounts (UncheckedAccount, CPI is no-op under mock-vrf)\n  { address: mockOraoProgram.publicKey, info: fundedAccountData() },\n  { address: mockOraoNetworkState.publicKey, info: fundedAccountData() },\n  { address: mockOraoTreasury.publicKey, info: fundedAccountData() },\n  // Mock randomness account — starts unfulfilled (32 zero bytes)\n  {\n    address: mockRandomness.publicKey,\n    info: {\n      lamports: LAMPORTS_PER_SOL,\n      data: RANDOMNESS_UNFULFILLED,\n      owner: SystemProgram.programId,\n      executable: false,\n    },\n  },\n]);\n```\n\n**Clock Manipulation (Lines 339-350):**\n```typescript\nasync function warpPastDeadline(t: TestContext) {\n  const clock = await t.context.banksClient.getClock();\n  t.context.setClock(\n    new Clock(\n      clock.slot + BigInt(300),\n      clock.epochStartTimestamp,\n      clock.epoch,\n      clock.leaderScheduleEpoch,\n      clock.unixTimestamp + BigInt(DEFAULT_RESOLVE_TIMEOUT + 10)\n    )\n  );\n}\n```\n\n**Mock Randomness Update (Lines 325-332):**\n```typescript\nfunction setMockRandomness(t: TestContext, data: Buffer) {\n  t.context.setAccount(t.mockRandomness.publicKey, {\n    lamports: LAMPORTS_PER_SOL,\n    data,\n    owner: SystemProgram.programId,\n    executable: false,\n  });\n}\n```\n\n**VRF State Tests (Lines 461-547):**\n- `join_match` sets `vrfRequestKey`, `resolveDeadline`, transitions to Locked\n- `claim_payout` validates `is_fulfilled` (byte[0] != 0), derives winner from randomness\n- `timeout_cancel` allows refund only when VRF unfulfilled and deadline passed\n\n**Key Lifecycle Tests (Lines 933-1009):**\n- Full create → join → claim flow with randomness\n- Timeout cancellation for unfulfilled VRF\n- Double-claim prevention (account closed)\n\n---\n\n## For Lord of RNGs Tests You Need To Add:\n\n1. **Mock VRF buffers** — same pattern as coinflip (randomness byte[0] determines result)\n2. **Mock Orao accounts** — same 3 mock Orao accounts + randomness account\n3. **Clock manipulation** — `warpPastDeadline()` for countdown testing\n4. **Mock randomness setter** — `setMockRandomness()` to fulfill VRF after test setup\n5. **Phase transition tests** — Waiting → Active (on 2nd join) → Locked (on spin request) → Resolved (on VRF fulfilled)\n6. **Idempotent pattern tests** — verify claim/timeout are single-entry (no double-settlement)\n\nThe coinflip tests are your blueprint—they handle all the VRF infrastructure you'll need."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a9b44bf (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 48926\ntool_uses: 2\nduration_ms: 17265</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"323ff130-207c-4bae-9ff2-11a67812c4db","uuid":"4c525709-3ce1-4e40-b8c7-496c0f56750f","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"I need to understand the existing test infrastructure for the lord of the rngs program. Please read these files and return their FULL contents:\n1. `sources/rng-utopia/solana/tests/lordofrngs.ts` — existing bankrun tests for lord\n2. `sources/rng-utopia/solana/tests/coinflip.ts` — coinflip tests (look for how VRF-related tests are structured, particularly `start_spin` or `place_bet` tests that involve Orao VRF mocking)\n\nReturn the full content of both files. Pay special attention to:\n- How mock VRF accounts are set up in bankrun\n- How the VRF request is tested\n- The idempotent pattern testing\n- How clock manipulation is done for countdown-based tests","agentId":"a9b44bf","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect! I've read both test files completely. Here's a summary of what I found:\n\n## Test Infrastructure Overview\n\n### **lordofrngs.ts** (Lines 1-541)\nThe Lord of RNGs tests are focused on **state transitions and escrow management**, NOT on VRF testing (since Lord doesn't use VRF in i